@NODE MSFontWB "Menu: Settings.Font WB-Screen"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

@{" x Standard Screen-Font " LINK ""}
@{" Select ...             " LINK ""}

The Submenu "Standard Screen-Font" changes the font used for the main
window into the standard Screenfont as set in the WB-Preferences.

The Submenu "Select ..." pops up a Font-Requester that let's you
choose the font you want to have for the main window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSFontEdit "Menu: Settings.Font Edit-Screen:
@TOC "ManualMenus"

@{" x Standard Screen-Font " LINK ""}
@{" Select ...             " LINK ""}

The Submenu "Standard Screen-Font" changes the font used on the Edit-
Screen into the standard Screenfont as set in the WB-Preferences.

The SubMenu "Select ..." pops up a Font-Requester that let's you
choose the font you want to have for the Edit-Screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSFontEditFix "Menu: Settings.Font Edit-Screen Fix"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

@{" x Topaz 8  " LINK ""}
@{" Select ... " LINK ""}

This menu controls the font used for certain things on the Edit-Screen
(such as PopUp-Menus and the Listview-Gadget in the Brush-Window)!

This font is of fixed width!

The SubMenu "Topaz 8" sets the font to topaz.font Size 8!

The SubMenu "Select ..."  pops up a Font-Requester!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSPicLoadRoutine "Menu: Settings.Pic-Load-Routine"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

@{" x Internal    " LINK ""}
@{"   Iff-Library " LINK ""}
@{"   Datatypes   " LINK ""}
@{"---------------" LINK ""}
@{"   ?           " LINK ""}
@{"   ?           " LINK ""}

Changes the Pic-Load-Routine. These are the possibilities:

- Internal	: Uses the built-in routine (only IFF-ILBM).
		  SUPPORTS MASK!

- Iff-Library	: Uses the iff.library.
		  NO MASK SUPPORT!!
			  
- Datatypes	: Loads all datatypes.
		  NO MASK SUPPORT!!
			  
- ?		: External Loaders read during Program-Startup from
		  the Directory "ExternalPL".
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSMaskBlitRoutine "Menu: Settings.Mask-Blit-Routine"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Changes the Maskblit-Routine. There are three possibilities:

@{" x OS Mode 1             " LINK ""}
@{"   OS Mode 2             " LINK ""}
@{"   BltMaskBitMapRastPort " LINK ""}

- OS Mode 1             : Works always

- OS Mode 2             : Works only if the mask "covers" ALL Pixels in the
		          Blocks-Picture that are of color 0 and NO Pixel of
	      		  Color <> 0. (You must have drawn the picture using
	      		  color 0 only for the parts which are masked! (If
	      		  you select the Menu @{"Mask/Create ..." LINK "MMCreate"} and select
	      		  color 0 as the color to mask then this routine
	      		  will work always)
		      
		          This Routine is faster than OS Mode 1
		      
- BltMaskBitMapRastPort : Uses BltMaskBitMapRastPort() for blitting. If you
			  want to use Non-Amiga Screenmodes (GFX-Board) this
			  Blit-Routine is probably the one you have to use
			  in order to get correct blittings. Further you
			  will have to change the Tooltypes:

			  @{" MASKBMF " LINK "TTMASKBMF"}  @{" PREZOOMMASKBMF " LINK "TTPREZOOMMASKBMF"}  @{" NOMASKFRIENDS " LINK "TTNOMASKFRIENDS"}


@{b}Note:@{ub} Does not work means that Blitting-Errors
      will/may occur!!
@ENDNODE
		      
@NODE MSAutoPoint "Menu: Settings.AutoPoint"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

@{" x Map Window   " LINK ""}
@{" x Tool Window  " LINK ""}
@{" x Brush Window " LINK ""}

Activates/Deactivates Autopoint for the following windows on Edit-Screen:

- Map Window
- Tool Window
- Brush Window

When ON Autopoint automatically activates the according window if you move
the mouse over it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MSEditCol" "Menu: Settings.Colors Edit-Screen"
@TOC "ManualMenus"
In this Sub-Menu you can control the way Powercrawler tries to achieve the
best looking GUI (only concerining Color-Usage) on Edit-Screen.

@{" x Edit-Extra-Plane " LINK "MSExtraPlane"}
@{" x Remap Color 0    " LINK "MSRemap0"}
@{"   Change Color 0   " LINK "MSChange0"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSPrecalcZoom "Menu: Settings.Precalc Zoom"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Activates/Deactivates Zoom-Pre-Calculation in Edit-Mode. Zoom-Pre-Calcu-
lation needs @{U}twice as much memory@{UU} but is considerably faster (depending
on the Zoom-Factor).

Check out the Tooltypes: @{" PREZOOMPICBMF=  " LINK "TTPreZoomPicBMF"}
			 @{" PREZOOMMASKBMF= " LINK "TTPreZoomMaskBMF"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSNoUndoBuffer "Menu: Settings.No Undo-Buffer"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Activates/Deactivates Undo-Buffer-Allocation. The Undo-Buffer needs the
same amount of memory as the Map-Buffer:

	Map-Width x Map-Height x Layers x Bytes per Block
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSProjectChange "Menu: Settings.Project-Changing..."
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Pops up a requester where you can select what to save into the temporary
files when you change the project. (There can be upto six projects)
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSTooltypes "Menu: Settings.Tooltypes ..."
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Pops up the Workbench Information-Window which allows you to change the
Tooltypes. So you don't need to quit and restart PowerCrawler each time
you want to change a Tooltype Setting.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSLoadDefault "Menu: Settings.Load Default"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Loads the default settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSLoadSettings "Menu: Settings.Load Settings ..."
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Pops up a File-Requester to load a Settings-File.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSSaveDefault "Menu: Settings.Save as default"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Saves the actual settings as default!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSSaveSettings "Menu: Settings. Save Settings ..."
@NEXT "MainMenuSettings"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

Pops up a File-Requester to save the actual settings into a Settings-File!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MSExtraPlane" "Menu: Settings.Extraplane"
@TOC "MSEditCol"
@PREV "MSEditCol"

Activates/Deactivates an Extraplane for the EditMode.

When ON the program tries to use one more plane for the Edit-Screen to
obtain a better Look of the GUI, because sometimes it can't find nice
colors because of the Block-Picture's palette. (It uses FindColor.)

	@{b}Note:@{ub} - Don't use this with HAM-Modes!!!!
	
	      - If you are using 256 colors (8 Planes) it won't work!
	        Nevertheless you don't have to care, it will check if
	        it is possible to or not!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MSRemap0" "Menu: Settings.Remap Color 0"
@TOC "MSEditCol"

Activates/Deactivates Color-0 Remapping.

When ON the program will remap color 0 of the Blocks-Picture. It will
replace it with the most similar color.

By doing this PowerCrawler can change the palette of Color 0 on the
Edit-Screen without changing the look of the Blocks too much. As Intuition
doesn't support BACKGROUNDPEN-Changing correctly this will help to obtain
a better look of the GUI on the Edit-Screen, because many times color 0
is used for Black and with a black BACKGROUNDPEN the GUI just doesn't look
good. It also causes Problems with the TEXTPEN which is also Black and
that leads to invisible texts.

When OFF the program changes the palette of Color 0 only for Requesters
and Setting-Windows.

If you turn it ON and there's a picture in memory which has not yet been
remapped then it will be automatically remapped (after User-Confirm if
User-Confirm is activated for Remapping!)
@ENDNODE

@NODE MSChange0 "Menu: Settings.Change Color 0"
@TOC "MSEditCol"
@NEXT "MSEditCol"

Activates/Deactivates BACKGROUNDPEN-Changing (DRIPENS). This is not suppor-
ted by Intuition but GadTools in some cases does support it.

@{b}Note:@{ub} If Color 0-Remapping is ON then this one has no function!!
@ENDNODE

