				       @{"   Change Pic-Mode        " LINK ""}
				       @{"--------------------------" LINK ""}
				       @{" x Change Map-Settings    " LINK ""}
				       @{" x Kill Mask              " LINK ""}
				       @{" x Kill Flip-Table        " LINK ""}
				       @{"--------------------------" LINK ""}
				       @{" x Overwrite Files        " LINK ""}


In this menu you can control for which operations you want to have
User-Confirmation.


o Quit Program

o New Project

o Load Picture 	 : If ON a Requester with some information about the
  (normal)         Picture (Width, Height, Colors, compression) will
                   appear. You can abort loading if you want to.
	                  
o Load Picture	 : When you load a project which contains the file-
  (Project)	   name of the Picture it will be loaded. If you
 		   want to confirm this then activate this item.
	 		  
o Remap Color 0  : When you activate Color 0-Remapping and there's a
		   picture in memory which is not remapped then
			  
		   - ON : you will be asked whether you want to re-
		          map it.
		   -OFF : it will be remapped!	 		  
	                  
o Change PicMode : When changing the Screenmode for the Block-Screen
                   in @{" Map-Settings " LINK "ManualMapSettings"} and there's actually a
                   picture in memory then
	                  
                   - ON : you will be asked whether you want the
                          ScreenMode to be changed or NOT.
	                         
                   -OFF : it will be changed
			  
		   @{B}Note :@{UB} ScreenMode-Changing of an already existing
		          Screen might not work!!!
 
o Change Settings: When changing the Map-Settings and there's a
                   Map-Buffer in memory then
	                  
                   - ON : you will be asked whether you want to
                          abort, convert the map or create a new
                          Buffer.
	                         
                   -OFF : it will be converted!
	                  
o Kill Mask      : Confirm when selecting @{"Menus/Mask.Kill" LINK "MMKill"}
			  
o Kill FlipTable : Confirm before killing the Flip-Buffer.

o Overwrite Files: Confirm when Save would overwrite existing File. 
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE MainMenuLoader "Menus: Loader"
@PREV "MainMenuConfirm"
@NEXT "MainMenuSaver"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

        @{" Project " LINK "MainMenuProject"} @{" Mask " LINK "MainMenuMask"} @{" Settings " LINK "MainMenuSettings"} @{" Confirm " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"} @{BG FILL}@{" Loader " LINK "MainMenuLoader"}@{BG BACKGROUND} @{" Saver " LINK "MainMenuSaver"}

						  @{" x Internal " LINK ""}
						  @{"------------" LINK ""}
						  @{"   ?        " LINK ""}
						  @{"   ?        " LINK ""}


Here you can choose which Routine to use for Map-Loading. The ones under
the barlabel are read during the Program-Startup from the Directory
"ExternalIO".

@{b}Note:@{ub} Project-Loading/Saving uses always the internal format!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MainMenuSaver "Menus: Saver"
@PREV "MainMenuLoader"
@NEXT "ManualMenus"
@TOC "ManualMenus"

        @{" Project " LINK "MainMenuProject"} @{" Mask " LINK "MainMenuMask"} @{" Settings " LINK "MainMenuSettings"} @{" Confirm " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"} @{" Loader " LINK "MainMenuLoader"} @{BG FILL}@{" Saver " LINK "MainMenuSaver"}@{BG BACKGROUND}

							    @{" x Internal " LINK ""}
							    @{"------------" LINK ""}
							    @{"   ?        " LINK ""}
							    @{"   ?        " LINK ""}


Here you can choose which Routine to use for Map-Saving. The ones under
the barlabel are read during the Program-Setup from the Directory
"ExternalIO".

@{b}Note:@{ub} Project-Loading/Saving uses always the internal format!
@ENDNODE


@NODE ManualGadgets "Main Window"
@TOC "Manual"
This is how the Main Window looks like:

		@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "Manual"}@{"PowerCrawler                       " LINK "ManualGadgets"}@{BG BACKGROUND}
                +-----------------------------------+
		| @{"  1  " LINK MGChange}@{"  2  " LINK MGChange}@{"  3  " LINK MGChange}@{"  4  " LINK MGChange}@{"  5  " LINK MGChange}@{"  6  " LINK MGChange} |
                +-----------------------------------+
		| @{"   Project   " LINK "MGProject"} @{"                  " LINK "ManualGadgets"} |
                +-----------------------------------+
		| @{"   Picture   " LINK "MGPicture"} @{"                  " LINK "ManualGadgets"} |
		| @{"     Map     " LINK "MGMap"} @{"                  " LINK "ManualGadgets"} |
		| @{"            Settings             " LINK "MGSettings"} |
                +-----------------------------------+
		| @{"  New Project   " LINK "MGNewProject"}@{"  Save Project  " LINK "MGSaveProject"} |
		| @{"   Edit Map     " LINK "MGEditMap"}@{"    Save Map    " LINK "MGSaveMap"} |
		| @{"  Information   " LINK "MGInformation"}@{"       Quit     " LINK "MGQuit"} |
                +-----------------------------------+

@{" Menus     " LINK "ManualMenus"}
@{" ShortCuts " LINK "MGShortCuts"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGShortCuts "Special Shortcuts in Main Window"
@PREV "ManualGadgets"
@NEXT "ManualGadgets"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

	- "1".. "6" @{" changes the Project " LINK "MGChange"}

	- <RETURN> - in a String-Gadget loads the Project, Picture or Map
	             depending in which String-Gadget you are without
	             popping up a File-Requester. The program will try to
	             load the file you have typed in.
	             
		   - outside any String-Gadget will activate @{" Edit Map " LINK "ManualEditingMaps"}

	- <SHIFT> + ShortCut of Project, Picture or Map will load taking the
	           filename from the according String-Gadget (no File-
	           Requester)

	- <SHIFT> + CLOSE-GADGET, QUIT-GADGET OR ESC iconifies PowerCrawler.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGChange "Gadget: Changing Project"
@PREV "ManualGadgets"
@NEXT "MGProject"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

The old project (the one active before activating the Gadget) will be saved
to a temporary file in Ram. The new project (the one you have selected)
will be either read from RAM: (if it had been editited earlier) or you get
a New Project (with all Buffers cleared!).

In @{" Menus/Projectchange " LINK "MSProjectChange"} you can edit what to save into the temporary
file in RAM:.

In the @{" Tooltypes " LINK "TTKillPrjBuffers"} you can select whether to delete the temporary files
in RAM: at End of Program or not.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MGProject "Gadget: Project"
@PREV "MGChange"
@NEXT "MGPicture"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up a File-Requester to load a Power-Crawler Project-File.
If ASKLOADPROJECT (see @{" Tooltypes " LINK "TTAskLoadProject"}) is not DEACTIVATED then if the file
was found a new @{" Window " LINK "ProjectWindow"} will pop up, where you can select which parts of
the project you want the program to load and which not!

If the Project-File contains the FileName of a Blocks-Picture than it will
be loaded automatically (after User-Confirm if set so in the @{" Confirm-Menu " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"}
(Item: Load Picture (Project)).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGPicture "Gadget: Picture"
@PREV "MGProject"
@NEXT "MGMap"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up a File-Requester to load a Picture using the Routine selected in
the Menu @{"Settings/Pic-Load-Routine" LINK "MSPicLoadRoutine"}. If you use the internal Routine
(only IFF-ILBM) then the mask (if exists) will also be loaded.

In the @{" Confirm-Menu " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"} you can select whether you want an Information-
window to pop up or not (Item: Load Picture (normal)). The Information-
Window also allows to abort loading.

@ENDNODE
		   	           
@NODE MGMap "Gadget: Map"
@PREV "MGPicture"
@NEXT "MGSettings"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up a File-Requester to load a Map-File using the Routine selected in
@{" Loader " LINK "MainMenuLoader"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGSettings "Gadget: Settings"
@PREV "MGMap"
@NEXT "MGNewProject"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Opens the @{" Map/ScreenMode-Settings Window " LINK "ManualMapSettings"}. In that window you can
change:

	- MapWidth, MapHeight
	
	- BlockWidth, BlockHeight
	
	- Number of Layers
	
	- Memory-Type (BYTE or WORD)
	
	- Transparent Block (0 or -1)
	
	- ScreenMode for Blocks-Picture-Screen
	
	- ScreenMode for Edit-Screen
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGNewProject "Gadget: New Project"
@PREV "MGSettings"
@NEXT "MGSaveProject"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Removes all data from memory (Picture, Map-Buffer, Flip-Buffer, ...). You
can select in the @{" Confirm-Menu " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"} whether you want to confirm this!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGSaveProject "Gadget: Save Project"
@PREV "MGNewProject"
@NEXT "MGEditMap"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up a @{" Window " LINK "ProjectWindow"} where you can select what you want the program to save
in the Project-File. If you confirm then a File-Requester will appear where
you can enter the FileName.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Even if in the Window that pops up you don't select anything, a file
      will be created. It will only contain the IFF-Header (12 Bytes).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGEditMap "Gadget: Edit Map"
@PREV "MGSaveProject"
@NEXT "MGSaveMap"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Enters the @{" Edit-Mode " LINK "ManualEditingMaps"}. In the @{" ToolTypes " LINK "TTCloseMainWindow"} you can select whether
the Main-Window shall be closed (while being in Edit-Mode) or not. Anyway
you won't be able to use it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MGSaveMap "Gadget: Save Map"
@PREV "MGEditMap"
@NEXT "MGInformation"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up a File-Requester to save the Map using the Routine selected in
@{" Menus/Saver " LINK "MainMenuSaver"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MGInformation"
@PREV "MGSaveMap"
@NEXT "MGQUIT"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Pops up an Information-Requester.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "MGQuit"
@PREV "MGInformation"
@NEXT "ManualGadgets"
@TOC "ManualGadgets"

Quits the program. If you want to confirm it look at the @{" Confirm-Menu " LINK "MainMenuConfirm"}
(Item: Quit Program).
@ENDNODE

@NODE ManualMapSettings "Map/Screenmode-Settings"
@TOC "Manual"
This is how the Map/ScreenMode-Settings Window looks like:

		@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "ManualGadgets"}@{"PowerCrawler: Settings          " LINK "ManualMapSettings"}@{BG BACKGROUND}
		+--------------------------------+
                |           Block-Size X - Y     |
		| @{"16  " LINK "MMSBlockX"} @{"                     " LINK "MMSBlockX"}@{"<" LINK "ManualMapSettings"}@{">" LINK "ManualMapSettings"} |
		| @{"16  " LINK "MMSBlockY"} @{"                     " LINK "MMSBlockY"}@{"<" LINK "ManualMapSettings"}@{">" LINK "ManualMapSettings"} |
		+------------+-------------------+
		|   Layers   | @{"100   " LINK "MMSLevelX"} Map-Width  |
	 	|    @{"1  " LINK "MMSLayers"}    | @{"100   " LINK "MMSLevelY"} Map-Height |
		|            |                   |
		| Transparent|   Byte @{" " LINK "MMSByte"}          |
	 	| @{" Block 0 " LINK "MMSTransp"} |           Mem-Type |
	        |            |   Word @{" " LINK "MMSWord"}          |
	        +------------+-------------------+
	        |                Screenmode      |
	        | @{"PICTURE" LINK "MMSPicture"} @{" 320 x 256 (21000)  " LINK "MMSModeInfo"}@{"<" LINK "MMSModeFromLevel"} |
	        | @{" EDIT  " LINK "MMSEdit"} @{" 320 x 256 (21000)  " LINK "MMSModeInfo"}@{"<" LINK "MMSModeFromPic"} |
	        +--------------------------------+
		| @{"   Confirm    " LINK "MMSConfirm"} @{"     Abort    " LINK "MMSAbort"} |
		+--------------------------------+

@{" Leaving the Window " LINK "MMSLeave"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSBlockX "Map/Screenmode-Settings: BlockSize-X"
@PREV "ManualMapSettings"
@NEXT "MMSBlockY"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can set the Block-Width (in Pixel).    @{b}(min. 1   max. 255)@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSBlockY "Map/Screenmode-Settings: BlockSize-Y"
@PREV "MMSBlockX"
@NEXT "MMSLayers"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can set the Block-Height (in Pixel).    @{b}(min.1   max. 255)@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSLayers "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Layers"
@PREV "MMSBlockY"
@NEXT "MMSTransp"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can set the number of Layers (not Parallax-Layers!). More than one
layer is only useful if there is a @{" Mask " LINK "ManualMask"}.    @{b}(min.1   max. 10)@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSTransp "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Transparent Block"
@PREV "MMSLayers"
@NEXT "MMSLevelX"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Whith this Cycle-Gadget you can select whether to use Block 0 or Block -1 as
the transparent Block. @{U}This has only effect if you are using more than one
Layer.@{UU}


The transparent Blocks in Layer #1 are filled rectangles in color 0.
The transparent Blocks in Layer #2,#3,... are not drawn (they are transpa-
rent and make visible the Blocks in the lower Layers).

See also @{" Mask " LINK "ManualMask"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSLevelX "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Map-Width X"
@PREV "MMSTransp"
@NEXT "MMSLevelY"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can set the Map-Width (in Blocks).   @{b}(min. 2   max. 32767)@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSLevelY "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Map-Width Y"
@PREV "MMSLevelX"
@NEXT "MMSByte"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can set the Map-Height (in Blocks).   @{b}(min.2   max. 32767)@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSByte "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Memorytype BYTE"
@PREV "MMSLevelY"
@NEXT "MMSWord"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Changes the Memorytype to BYTE. Each Block will be represented by a Number
between 0 and 255. So the maximal number of different Blocks you can use
in the Map is 256!

Needs ONE Byte per Block when saving!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSWord "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Memorytype WORD"
@PREV "MMSByte"
@NEXT "MMSPicture"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Changes the Memorytype to WORD. Each Block will be represented by a Number
between 0 and 65535. So the maximal number of different Blocks you can use
in the Map is 65536.

Needs TWO Bytes per Block when saving!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSPicture "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Screenmode Picture-Screen"
@PREV "MMSWord"
@NEXT "MMSEdit"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Pops up a Screenmode-Requester to change the Screenmode for the Blocks-
Screen.

@{b}Note:@{ub} You have to set the Screenmode BEFORE loading any Picture, because
      the Loading-Routines DON'T CHANGE the Screenmode-Settings. So if
      your actual Screenmode is LOWRES 320 x 256 x 256 COLS and you try to
      load a HAM-Picture it won't be displayed correctly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSEdit "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Screenmode Edit-Screen"
@PREV "MMSPicture"
@NEXT "MMSConfirm"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Pops up a Screenmode-Requester to change the Screenmode for the Edit-
Screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSConfirm "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Confirm"
@PREV "MMSEdit"
@NEXT "MMSAbort"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Confirms the Settings. This can also be done by pressing the Right Mouse-
Button or by pressing the Close-Gadget of the window.

Look at @{" Leaving the Window " LINK "MMSLeave"}!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSAbort "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Abort"
@PREV "MMSConfirm"
@NEXT "ManualMapSettings"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Aborts. You will get the previous Settings!

@{B}Note:@{UB} If you have changed a Screenmode-Setting it will NOT be restored!
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSModeInfo "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Mode Info"
@PREV "ManualMapSettings"
@NEXT "ManualMapSettings"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Here you can see some info about the selected ScreenMode in the following
Format:

	<@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Visible-Size X@{FG TEXT}> x <@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Visible-Size Y@{FG TEXT}> ( <@{FG HIGHLIGHT}Display-ID@{FG TEXT}> )

@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSModeFromLevel "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Set to Edit's Screenmode"
@PREV "ManualMapSettings"
@NEXT "MMSModeFromPic"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Copies the Edit Screenmode Settings to the Picture's ones.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSModeFromPic "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Set to Pictures's Screenmode"
@PREV "MMSModeFromLevel"
@NEXT "ManualMapSettings"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

Copies the Picture Screenmode Settings to the Edit's ones.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MMSLeave "Map/Screenmode-Settings: Leaving"
@PREV "ManualMapSettings"
@NEXT "ManualMapSettings"
@TOC "ManualMapSettings"

When leaving the Settings-Window by pressing the Right Mouse-Button, the
Confirm-Gadget or the Window's Close-Gadget then: 

	- If there's no Map-Buffer nothing will happen. The Map-Buffer will
	  be created when:

	  	- You load a Mapfile
	  	
	  	- You load a Projectfile which contains a Map-Buffer
	  	
	  	- You enter Edit-Mode the first time.
	  	
	  It will not be created if you just change some settings but have
	  never entered the Edit-Mode (or loaded a Mapfile/Projectfile with
	  Mapbuffer).
	  
	- If there's a Map-Buffer then:

		- If no setting has changed, nothing will happen.

		- If one or more settings have changed a Requester will
		  appear that asks you whether you want to:

		  	o Convert the Map-Buffer. If the new Buffer's Width
		  	  (MapWidth) is lower than the old one's the right
		  	  part will be cut!! If the new Buffer's Height is
		  	  lower than the old one's the bottom part will be
		  	  cut!!

		  	o Create a new Buffer. The old one will be killed
		  	  and a new (BLANK) one will be created.

		  	o Abort. The old Settings will be used and no
		  	  change to the Map-Buffer will be done.

		  @{b}Note:@{ub} The Requester won't appear if the according Check-
		  	mark in @{"Menus/Confirm" LINK "MainMenuConfirm"} isn't set!
		  	In this case the program WILL CONVERT the map auto-
		  	matically!!
@ENDNODE
		  	
@NODE Manual "How to use PowerCrawler"

When you first start PowerCrawler you will see the main window which always
appears on the Workbench-Screen. From here you can load/save Maps, Pictures
(Blocks), change the settings (LevelSize, ScreenModes, Fonts ...) and of
course access the Edit-Mode.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Editing is always done on a screen apart. When you are in Edit-Mode
      then the Main-Window cannot be used (it is inactive). For example if
      you are editing your map and want to save it, then you have to leave
      Edit-Mode first!
     
     				@{" GUI-Note     " LINK "ManualGUI"}
                                @{" Concept      " LINK "ManualConcept"}

                                @{FG SHINE}@{" Main Window  " LINK "ManualGadgets"}@{FG TEXT}
                                @{" Main Menus   " LINK "ManualMenus"}
				@{" Map-Settings " LINK "ManualMapSettings"}
 				
				@{FG SHINE}@{" Editing Maps " LINK "ManualEditingMaps"}@{FG TEXT}
			        @{" Tooltypes    " LINK "Tooltypes"}
--> @{" Tips.readme " LINK "Tips.readme/Main"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE TooltypesReadme "Some info about the Tooltypes"
@TOC "Tooltypes"
@NEXT "Tooltypes"
@PREV "Tooltypes"

o The boolean Tooltypes (those with no parameter):

	- take the default value (TRUE or FALSE) if they don't appear in
	  the Tooltypes or are closed in brackets: for example: (NEWPROP)
	  
	- are TRUE if they appear in the Tooltypes (without brackets) 
	  without any <=????>
	  
	- are TRUE if they appear in the Tooltypes in the following way:

	  	<Tooltype>=????
	  	
	  	@{b}Note:@{ub} ???? must NOT be one of the names you see below!!
	  	           ("OFF","NO","0", ...)

			   For example you could write:
			   
			   	<Tooltype>=YES
			   	<Tooltype>=1
			   	<Tooltype>=TRUE
			   	<Tooltype>=nAtURALmente
			   	<Tooltype>=Amiga
			   	
			   to make them TRUE!
			   
	- are FALSE if they appear in the Tooltypes in one of the following
	  ways:
	  
		<Tooltype>=FALSE
	  	<Tooltype>=OFF
	  	<Tooltype>=NO
	  	<Tooltype>=AUS
	  	<Tooltype>=NEIN
	  	<Tooltype>=0

o The tooltypes taking a numeric parameter must appear in one of the
  following ways (otherwise they get the default value):
  
  	- <Tooltype>=<Decimal-Number>	( for example: FILLBUFFERS=100)
  	
  	- <Tooltype>=0x<Hex. Number>	( for example: FILLBUFFERS=0x60)
  	  <Tooltype>=0X<Hex. Number>	( "   "      : FILLBUFFERS=0X60)

o When editing the Tooltypes (for the first time) you will see that by
  default they are all inactive (closed in brackets). They are listed
  in the following Format:

  (@{FG SHINE}TOOLTYPE@{FG TEXT}=@{FG SHINE}DEFAULT PARAMETER@{FG TEXT} [@{FG SHINE}POSSIBLE PARAMETERS@{FG TEXT}])

  @{B}Example:@{UB} (CLICKMODE1=1 [1,2]) means:

  	   By default CLICKMODE1 has the value 1. The possible values are
  	   1 and 2.

  @{B}Note:@{UB}    - <A>..<B> means Range from <A> to <B>
           - Boolean Tooltypes don't have the [@{FG SHINE}POSSIBLE PARAMETERS@{FG TEXT}]-Part


o Tooltypes with a special parameter are described in @{" Tooltype-Docs " LINK "Tooltypes"}!


@ENDNODE
	  	
