@NODE TTNewProp "Tooltypes: NEWPROP"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE the look of the GadTools Proportional-gadgets will be changed.
This is a hack. It sets PROPNEWLOOK in the Gadget-Flags!
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTScaleMX "Tooltypes: SCALEMX"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, MUTUAL-EXCLUDE-Gadgets are scaled in relation to the Font's
  Height and Width.
  
o If FALSE, they get the standard Width/Height.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTScaleCB "Tooltypes: SCALECB"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, CHECKBOX-Gadgets are scaled in relation to the Font's Width and
  Height.
  
o If FALSE, they get the standard Width/height.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTScaleAR "Tooltypes: SCALEAR"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, the ARROW-Buttons (of SLIDER- and SCROLLER-Gadgets) are scaled
  in relation to the Font's Width or Height.
  
o If FALSE, they get the default size.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TTHighLabel "Tooltypes: HIGHLABEL"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, the Labels of the Gadgets will be drawn with the HIGHLIGHTTEXT-
  PEN (usually White).

o If FALSE the Labels are drawn with the TEXTPEN.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTFrameType "Tooltypes: FRAMETYPE="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 1,2,3
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 1

Description:

Changes the type of the Bevel-Boxes used in most Windows:

	1 = BUTTON
	2 = RIDGE
	3 = ICONDROPBOX
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTFrameDepth "Tooltypes: FRAMEDEPTH"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE the Bevel-Boxes in the Windows are drawn in RECESSED-Mode.

o If FALSE they are not.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TTXen "Tooltypes: XEN"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE the Button-Gadgets get a Black Frame around them to achieve a nicer
look.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNiceString "Tooltypes: NICESTRING"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, the String-Gadgets (Text and Integer) change their look when
being active (the Background becomes white).
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTDisableGadgets "Tooltypes: DISABLEGADGETS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

If TRUE, when entering the Map/Screenmode-Settings Window or a Screenmode/
Font/File-Requester the gadgets of the Main Window will be disabled!
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTCalcFontX "Tooltypes: CALCFONTX"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

PowerCrawler takes the Font's tf_XSize and tf_YSize to scale the GUI. This
results in a very simple form of Font Sensitivity. If you are using a pro-
portional Font then tf_XSize is just a generic value which sometimes is
rather good for X-Scaling but in many cases the value of tf_XSize instead
of being an average-value is just to low or to high. Therefore PowerCrawler
by default takes a certain number of Strings and calcs its' Length in Pixels
by using TextLength(). The biggest resulting Scale-Factor (= Pixel_Length /
String_Length) will be used.

If you want PowerCrawler to use tf_XSize to Scale the GUI set this to FALSE.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTSafeLoadIff "Tooltypes: SAFELOADIFF"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

Changes the way the internal IFF-Load-Routine works:

o If TRUE the Routine uses Planar to Chunky Conversion and WritePixelLine8.
  This should work always (with GFX-Boards too)!
  
o If FALSE the Routine copys the Planar Data in the Iff-File to a Standard-
  Bitmap (see @{" LOADIFFBMF " LINK "TTLoadIffBMF"}). This is done using a simple CopyMem. After that
  the Routine makes a BltBitmap from this Bitmap to the Picture-Screen.
  
  This is not really OS-conform and may cause problems on GFX-Boards, but
  on Machines with no GFX-Board it is FASTER.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTPicInterleaved "Tooltypes: PICINTERLEAVED"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

Defines whether to open the Picture-Screen in Interleaved-Mode or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTMapInterleaved "Tooltypes: MAPINTERLEAVED"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

Defines whether to open the Map-Preview-Screen in Interleaved-Mode or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTEditInterleaved "Tooltypes: EDITINTERLEAVED"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

Defines whether to open the Edit Screen in Interleaved-Mode or not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTLoadIffBMF "Tooltypes: LOADIFFBMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 12             ( = BMF_STANDARD+BMF_INTERLEAVED)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the Bitmap alloced by the internal Iff-Loader if
@{" SAFELOADIFF " LINK "TTSafeLoadIff"} is FALSE!

@{b}Note: @{ub}The Result must be a Bitmap in Planar-Format.

	BMF_CLEAR       = 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD    = 8
	BMF_MINPLANES   = 16
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTMaskBMF "Tooltypes: MASKBMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the Bitmap used for the Mask.

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

If you want to use Non-Amiga Screenmodes (GFX-Board) you probably have
to set BMF_STANDARD. Try setting this Tooltype to 24 (BMF_STANDARD +
BMF_MINPLANES).
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTTempBMF "Tooltypes: TEMPBMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for temporary allocated Bitmaps needed for WritePixel-
Line8, WritePixelLine8, ...

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

@ENDNODE

@NODE TTOneBlock1BMF "Tooltypes: ONEBLOCK1BMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the first One-Block-Bitmap which has the Width/Height
of one Block. This Bitmap is needed for Mask-Blitting and scaled Blitting.

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

See @{" BlockBlit-Routine " LINK "BlockBlitRoutine"}!
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTOneBlock2BMF "Tooltypes: ONEBLOCK2BMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the second One-Block-Bitmap which has the Width/Height
of one Block. This Bitmap is needed for Mask-Blitting and scaled Blitting.

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

See @{" BlockBlit-Routine " LINK "BlockBlitRoutine"}!
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTPreZoomPicBMF "Tooltypes: PREZOOMPICBMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the Picture-Bitmap used when Zoom-Precalc is on.

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

@ENDNODE

@NODE TTPreZoomMaskBMF "Tooltypes: PREZOOMMASKBMF="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20		   ( = BMF_INTERLEAVED+BMF_MINPLANES)

Description:

Changes the Flags for the Mask-Bitmap used when Zoom-Precalc is on.

	BMF_CLEAR 	= 1
	BMF_DISPLAYABLE = 2
	BMF_INTERLEAVED = 4
	BMF_STANDARD	= 8
	BMF_MINPLANES	= 16

If you want to use Non-Amiga Screenmodes (GFX-Board) you probably have
to set BMF_STANDARD. Try setting this Tooltype to 24 (BMF_STANDARD +
BMF_MINPLANES).
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTWaitBlit "Tooltypes: WAITBLIT"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, a WaitBlit-Call is done before any:

	ClipBlit, BltBitmap, BltBitmapRastPort!

@{b}Might be necessary for GFX-Boards.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNoFriends "Tooltypes: NOFRIENDS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, the AllocBitmap-Calls set FriendBitmap to NULL.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNoMaskFriends "Tooltypes: NOMASKFRIENDS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

if TRUE, the Mask-Bitmaps will be alloced without stating a Friend Bitmap.
If you want to use Non-Amiga Screenmodes (GFX-Boards) you will probably
have to set this to TRUE.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNiceMarking "Tooltypes: NICEMARKING"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

If TRUE, when doing a Selection in Edit-Mode (for example to pick up a
Brush) the rectangle which marks the Area will be drawn with a scrolling
pattern.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTBigDrag "Tooltypes: BIGDRAG"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

o If TRUE the Special-Window (Box at the bottom) on the Edit-Screen gets a
  Drag-Gadget as big as the window itself. So you can click anywhere to
  change its position (except you don't click on a Gadget).

o If FALSE the Special-Window can only be moved by clicking on its DragBar
  at the left side of the Window.
   
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTAutoFront "Tooltypes: AUTOFRONT"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

o If TRUE, when selecting a Block (or a Group of Blocks) on the Blocks-
  Screen the program will automatically bring to front the Edit-Screen.
  
o If FALSE you will remain on the Blocks-Screen and will have to use
  the Right Mouse Button or <SPACE> to get to the Edit-Screen!  
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTClickMode1 "Tooltypes: CLICKMODE1="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 1  2  DRAG  RELEASE
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 1

Description:

Changes the way some Drawing-Functions (those who take 2 coordinates) in
Edit-Mode are handled:

1, DRAG	   : - CLICK LEFT MOUSE BUTTON (hold LMB)
	     - MOVE MOUSE (hold LMB)
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSE BUTTON

	       @{b}CLICK - MOVE - RELEASE@{ub}


2, RELEASE : - CLICK LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - MOVE MOUSE (no Mouse-Button pressed);
	     - CLICK LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     
	       @{b}CLICK - RELEASE - MOVE - CLICK - RELEASE @{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTClickMode2 "Tooltypes: CLICKMODE2="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 1  2  DRAG  RELEASE
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 1

Description:

Changes the way Picking up Blocks (on the Block-Screen) is handled:

1, DRAG	   : - CLICK LEFT MOUSE BUTTON (hold LMB)
	     - MOVE MOUSE (hold LMB)
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSE BUTTON

	       @{b}CLICK - MOVE - RELEASE@{ub}


2, RELEASE : - CLICK LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - MOVE MOUSE (no Mouse-Button pressed);
	     - CLICK LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     - RELEASE LEFT MOUSEBUTTON
	     
	       @{b}CLICK - RELEASE - MOVE - CLICK - RELEASE @{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTPopUpSettings "Tooltypes: POPUPSETTINGS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, the Settings-Windows of the Drawmodes (LINE, AIRBRUSH, FILL),
  the CLR-Window and the Zoom-Settings-Window will get a BORDERLESS Window
  and will look like a POPUP-WINDOW (because they pop up near the gadget).

o If FALSE the Windows mentioned above will have a standard Look and will
  be centered on the Screen.  
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTInactiveClose "Tooltypes: INACTIVECLOSE"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

o If TRUE, most Requesters (but not the System ones) can be aborted/leaved
  by DEACTIVATING them (clicking outside the window).
  
o If FALSE, this isn't possible.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TTToolNoBorder "Tooltypes: TOOLNOBORDER"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, the Toolwindow on the Edit-Screen will get a borderless Window.

o If FALSE, the Toolwindow gets a normal Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTMarkingticks "Tooltypes: MARKINGTICKS="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 8

Description:

This Tooltype controls the number of Intui-Ticks that must expire before in
Edit-Mode the Cursor=Marker (a Rectangle with two diagonal lines) turns into
a Super-Cursor.

What for hell is a Super-Cursor??? Well for reasons of speed the program
usually only draws a rectangle with two diagonal lines in the Map-Window
to show where the actual Block will be drawn. But if you have picked up a
big Group of Blocks or you have a big Brush you often don't know if it will
be put at the right place, so if you don't touch your Mouse/Keyboard for a
certain period of time (controlled by MARKINGTICKS) the program will draw
the Block/Brush temporary. As soon as you touch the the Mouse/Keyboard
again it will turn into a normal Cursor.

@{b}Note:@{ub} A value of 0 causes the program to use only the normal Cursor.
      Of course when you select the Super-Cursor to be active "@{U}ALWAYS@{UU}" in
      the @{" Edit-Menus " LINK "EMSuperCursor"} you will get a Super-Cursor.

      @{B}MARKINGTICKS@{UB} just sets the delay for "@{U}STANDARD DELAY@{UU}".
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTRelZoom "Tooltypes: RELZOOM="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMBER
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 1 .. 100
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 20

Description:

Defines the relative Zoom-Factor that is applied when pressing <+> or <->
or LMB with ALT-RIGHT / ALT-RIGHT+SHIFT-RIGHT hold down in the Map-Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTForceLocale "Tooltypes: FORCELOCALE"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, PowerCrawler tries to load a Catalog-File for the BuiltIn-Language
(English). So if you want to change the Shortcuts or don't like my terrible
English set this to TRUE and create your own Catalog. (The Catalog-Descrip-
tion and Catalog-Translation Files are in the directory "catalogs"!)
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNoLocale "Tooltypes: NOLOCALE"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, PowerCrawler will be forced to use the BUILT-IN-LANGUAGE.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNoMapIcons "Tooltypes: NOMAPICONS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, no Icon will be created when saving a Map.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTNoPrjIcons "Tooltypes: NOPRJICONS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

If TRUE, no Icon will be created when saving a Project.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTIconifyX "Tooltypes: ICONIFYX="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMBER
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} -1 (means NO_ICON_POSITION)

Description:

Sets the X-Position of the Iconify-Icon.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTIconifyY "Tooltypes: ICONIFYY="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMBER
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} -1 (means NO_ICON_POSITION)

Description:

Sets the Y-Position of the Iconify-Icon.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTAskLoadProject "Tooltypes: ASKLOADPROJECT"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

If TRUE, when loading a Project, a window will pop up that shows you what
kind of data the Project contains (Map-Buffer, Flip-Table, Brushes, ...).
You can decide which of the data you want to load and which not.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTCloseMainWindow "Tooltypes: CLOSEMAINWINDOW"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

o If TRUE, when entering the Edit-Mode, the Main Window will be closed.

o If FALSE, when entering the Edit-Mode, the Main Window remains open but
  nevertheless can't be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTFillBuffers "Tooltypes: FILLBUFFERS="
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} NUMERIC
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 11..999
@{b}Default   :@{ub} 100

Description:

Controls the Number of Fill-Buffers used for Filling-Operations. One Fill-
Buffer needs some hundred bytes. You need a big amount of Fill-Buffers only
if you want to fill very complex Forms. Usually for a normal Fill-Operation
the program doesn't need more than 15 Fill-Buffers.

@{b}Note:@{ub} If for a  Fill-Operation there aren't enough Fill-Buffers the only
      thing that will happen is that the filling is not complete.
      
      The FillBuffers are allocated at any Fill-Operation and freed at the
      finish of this operation!
      
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTKillPrjBuffers "Tooltypes: KILLPRJBUFFERS"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub} 
@{b}Default   :@{ub} TRUE

Description:

Usually the temporary files (which are Project-Files) in RAM: will be
deleted when you quit the program. If you don't want that for some reason
then set KILLPRJBUFFERS to FALSE!
@ENDNODE

@NODE TTExpandpath "Tooltypes: EXPANDPATH"
@NEXT "Tooltypes"
@TOC "Tooltypes"

@{b}Type      :@{ub} BOOLEAN
@{b}Parameter :@{ub}
@{b}Default   :@{ub} FALSE

Description:

Defines whether Filenames shall be expanded or not. If you want to use re-
lative Paths <EXPANDPATH> must be FALSE.

@{B}Expample for EXPANDPATH:@{UB}

	Current Directory = <Work:PowerCrawler>

	<pictures/Demo.iff>  @{I}becomes@{UI}  <Work:PowerCrawler/pictures/Demo.iff>
	<dh1:MyMap>          @{I}becomes@{UI}  <Work:MyMap>
	</Test>              @{I}becomes@{UI}  <Work:Test>
@ENDNODE



@NODE BlockBlitRoutine "The way PowerCrawler does the Block-Blitting"
@TOC "ToolTypes"
@NEXT "ToolTypes"
@PREV "ToolTypes"

First some info about the Mask. The Mask is a Bitmap with the same Width,
Height and number of Planes the Blocks-Picture has. In the Mask there can
be only two different "colors" (not really colors, but "Bit-Combinations").
For example if your Picture has 32 Colors (5 Planes) then in the Mask each
Point being a Mask-Point is of Color 31 (All BitPlanes set) and each Point
beeing a NonMask-Point is of Color 0 (All BitPlanes cleared).
@{b}
> The Mask is 0 if the Pixel of the Block SHALL NOT BE transparent.
> The Mask is -1 (or 2^Planes - 1) if the Pixel of the Block SHALL BE
  transparent!
@{ub}
o For normal Blitting (without Mask) Powercrawler does a BltBitmapRastPort
  from the PictureScreen-Bitmap to the EditScreen-Window.
  
o For MaskBlitting Powercrawler does this:

	@{" OS Mode 1 " LINK "MSMaskBlitRoutine"} :

	BltBitmapRastPort(PictureBitmap,a,b,OneBlock1RastPort,0,0,Width,Height,192)
	@{i}(Copy the Block to OneBlock1Bitmap)@{ui}

	BltBitmapRastPort(MaskBitmap,a,b,OneBlock1RastPort,0,0,Width,Height,ANBC)
	@{i}(Clear points in OneBlockBitmap where Mask is set)@{ui}

	BltBitmapRastPort(MaskBitmap,a,b,EditWindowRastPort,x,y,Width,Height,ABC)
	@{i}(Clear points in EditWindow (Destination) where Mask is not set)@{ui}

	BltBitmapRastPort(OneBlock1Bitmap,0,0,EditWindowRastPort,x,y,Width,Height,$EE)
	@{i}(OneBlockBitmap OR EditWindowRastPort)@{ui}

	@{" OS Mode 2 " LINK "MSMaskBlitRoutine"} :

	BltBitmapRastPort(MaskBitmap,a,b,EditWindowRastPort,x,y,Width,Height,ABC)
	@{i}(Clear points in EditWindow (Destination) where Mask is not set)@{ui}

	BltBitmapRastPort(PictureBitmap,a,b,EditWindowRastPort,x,y,Width,Height,$EE)
	@{i}(PictureBitmap OR EditWindowRastport)@{ui}

	@{" BltMaskBitMapRastPort " LINK "MSMaskBlitRoutine"} :

	BltMaskBitMapRastPort(PitcureBitmap,a,b,EditWindowRastPort,x,y,Width,Height,184,MaskBitmap->Planes[0])


@{b}Note:@{ub} I don't know if this works on GFX-Boards. If you know a better/faster
      way of doing Mask-Blitting then let me know.

@ENDNODE

