@NODE EditToolNotes "Edit-Screen: Tool-Window.Notes"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

o The following Draw-Tools have a Settings-Window. You can access it by
  clicking on the gadget when it is already active (no real Double-Click.
  Just click twice on the same Gadget!)
  
	- @{"   Line   " LINK "LineSettings"}
	- @{"   Fill   " LINK "FillSettings"}
	- @{" Airbrush " LINK "AirSettings"}

o There's a hidden Zoom-Gadget at the right bottom edge of the Window. So
  if you want to scale the Tool-Gadgets just click there.
  
o To access the @{" Brush-Window " LINK "BrushWindow"} (where you can add the actual Brush to the
  Brush-Table which can be @{" saved " LINK "MGSaveProject"}) press twice F2 or click twice the
  @{" BrushMode-Gadget " LINK "EditToolBrush"}!
  
o Have a look at the @{" Shortcuts " LINK "EditShortCuts"}!;
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolBlock "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Block-Mode"
@NEXT "EditToolBrush"
@PREV "EditToolWindow"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: F1

Activates the Block-Mode. When you pick up a Block or a group of Blocks from
the Blocks-Screen then Block-Mode will be activated automatically. If you
@{" cut " LINK "EditToolCut"} a Brush or select one in the Brush-PopUp-Menu then @{" Brush-Mode " LINK "EditToolBrush"} will
be activated automatically.

Therefore you usually don't need to access this Gadget. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolBrush "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Brush-Mode"
@PREV "EditToolBlock"
@NEXT "EditToolReplace"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: F2

Activates the Brush-Mode. When you pick up a Block or a group of Blocks from
the Blocks-Screen then @{" Block-Mode " LINK "EditToolBlock"} will be activated automatically. If you
@{" cut " LINK "EditToolCut"} a Brush or select one in the Brush-PopUp-Menu then Brush-Mode will
be activated automatically.

Therefore you usually have to access this gadget only if you have picked up
a Brush earlier but after that have picked up a Block from the Blocks-
Screen and now you want to use that Brush again.

By clicking twice on the Brush-Mode-Gadget the @{" Brush-Window " LINK "BrushWindow"} will pop
up!
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolReplace "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Replace-Mode"
@PREV "EditToolBrush"
@NEXT "EditToolMatte"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: F6

Activates the Replace-Mode. In this Mode any Block/Group of Blocks/Brush
will be drawn into the actual Layer (and the following ones if you are
using a Brush with more than one Layer!) @{B}replacing any Blocks that were
in the Layer/s.@{UB} Use the @{" Menus " LINK "EditMenuSettings"} to select whether you want transparent
Blocks to be drawn or not. (Item: Transparent Block --> If it is activated
then transparent Blocks will NOT be drawn otherwise they will be!).
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolMatte "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Matte-Mode"
@PREV "EditToolReplace"
@NEXT "EditToolLine"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: F7

Activates the Matte-Mode. In this Mode any Block/Group of Blocks/Brush
will be drawn into the actual Layer (and the following ones if you are
using a Brush with more than one Layer!) @{B}affecting only Blocks which
are transparent!!.@{UB}

@{B}Note:@{UB} If you are using only one Layer then Matte-Mode has no sense!

@{B}Example:@{UB}

- Your Map has 7 Layers.
- Transparent Block is Block #0;
- Your Brush is 1 Block x 1 Block x 5 Layers and looks like this:

	Layer:       Block-Number
	»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»
	  1              101
	  2              102
	  3              103
	  4              104
	  5              105
	  
- The map at the Position you want to put the Brush looks like this:

	Layer:       Block-Number
	»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»
	  1              201
	  2              202
	  3                0 <transparent>
	  4              204
	  5                0 <transparent>
	  6                0 <transparent>
	  7                0 <transparent>
	  
After putting the Brush the map will look like this:

	Layer:       Block-Number
	»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»
	  1              201
	  2              202
	  3              101 <from Brush Layer 1>
	  4              204
	  5              102 <from Brush Layer 2>
	  6              103 <from Brush Layer 3>
	  7              104 <from Brush Layer 4>
	  
@{I}As you see above Layer 5 of the Brush could not be drawn because there
weren't enough transparent Blocks in the Map!@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolFree "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Freehand"
@PREV "EditToolMatte"
@NEXT "EditToolLine"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: D

Sets the DrawTool to Freehand.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Freehand-Drawing.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-MOVING
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-MOVING

@{I}The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to draw!@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolLine "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Line"
@PREV "EditToolFree"
@NEXT "EditToolRect"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: V

Sets the DrawTool to Line.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Line-Marking.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-MOVING
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-MOVING
    - ALT-LEFT to lock Angle if X-Offset (Vector) is greater than
      Y-Offset (Vector). 
    - ALT-RIGHT to lock Angle if Y-Offset (Vector) is greater than
      X-Offset (Vector).
    - RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON to abort Line-Marking.
    - <+> to increase Zoom-Factor during Line-Marking.
    - <-> do decrease Zoom-Factor during Line-Marking.

By clicking twice the Line-Gadget you enter a @{" Settings-Window " LINK "LineSettings"}!

@{I}The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to draw the Line.
You should use @{" Matte-Mode " LINK "EditToolMatte"} only if you are drawing in
One-Point per Row/Column-Mode (see @{" Settings-Window " LINK "LineSettings"}!)@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolRect "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Rectangle"
@PREV "EditToolLine"
@NEXT "EditToolRectF"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: R

Sets the DrawTool to Rectangle.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Rectangle-Marking.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-Moving
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-Moving
    - ALT to make the Height equal to the Width
    - <RETURN> to select the whole map.
    - RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON to abort Rectangle-Marking.
    - <+> to increase Zoom-Factor during Rectangle-Marking.
    - <-> to decrease Zoom-Factor during Rectangle-Marking.

@{I}The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to draw the Rect-
angle.@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolRectF "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Filled Rectangle"
@PREV "EditToolRect"
@NEXT "EditToolAirB"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: <SHIFT> R

Sets the DrawTool to Filled Rectangle.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Rectangle-Marking.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-Moving
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-Moving
    - ALT to make the Height equal to the Width
    - <RETURN> to select the whole map.
    - RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON to abort Rectangle-Marking.
    - <+> to increase Zoom-Factor during Rectangle-Marking.
    - <-> to decrease Zoom-Factor during Rectangle-Marking.
    
@{I}The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to draw the filled
Rectangle!@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolAirB "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Airbrush"
@PREV "EditToolRectF"
@NEXT "EditToolFill"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: A

Sets the DrawTool to Airbrush.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Air-Brushing.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-Moving
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-Moving
    
By clicking twice the Airbrush-Gadget you enter a @{" Settings-Window " LINK "AirSettings"}!

@{I} The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to draw!@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolFill "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Fill"
@PREV "EditToolAirB"
@NEXT "EditToolCut"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: F

Sets the DrawTool to Fill.

By clicking twice the Fill-Gadget you enter a @{" Settings-Window " LINK "FillSettings"}!
Check out the Tooltype @{" FILLBUFFERS " LINK "TTFillBuffers"}!.

@{I}The actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush will be used to fill!@{UI}
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolCut "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Cut"
@PREV "EditToolFill"
@NEXT "EditToolClear"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: b

Sets the DrawTool to Brush-Cutting.

Use - CURSORKEYS to scroll the Map during Range-Marking.
    - SHIFT-LEFT to lock Y-Moving
    - SHIFT-RIGHT to lock X-Moving
    - ALT to make the Height equal to the Width
    - <RETURN> to select the whole map.
    - RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON to abort Range-Marking.
    - <+> to increase Zoom-Factor during Range-Marking.
    - <-> to decrease Zoom-Factor during Range-Marking.


@{B}Hint:@{UB}

If you hold down the RIGHT AMIGA-KEY while selecting the first point of the
Range, as soon as the Range-Selection is done a Window will appear where
you can give a Name to the Brush which will be added to the Brush-Table
immediately. This is very useful if you have to cut a lot of Brushes that
you want to add to the Brush-Table.


@{B}Important:@{UB} o The Brush will be cut from the actual and all following
             Layers. Example: If your Map has 5 Layers and your actual Layer
             is 2 then the Brush will have 4 Layers (Layer 2,3,4,5 of the
             Map)!!
           o The Brush will get the Name "<noname>" till you add it to the
             Brush-Table (this is done in the @{" Brush-Window " LINK "BrushWindow"}!)
           o After having done a Cut the DrawTool will become the Tool
             active before activating the Cut-Gadget.

Check out the Tooltype @{" NICEMARKING " LINK "TTNiceMarking"}!
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolClear "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Clear"
@PREV "EditToolCut"
@NEXT "EditToolUndo"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: <SHIFT> K

Pops up the Clear-Window which looks like this:

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditToolWindow"}@{"Clear                                  " LINK "EditToolClear"}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	|       Range       |        Layers     |
	| @{" " LINK "EditToolClear"} All            | @{" " LINK "EditToolClear"} All             |
	| @{" " LINK "EditToolClear"} View           | @{" " LINK "EditToolClear"} Actual          |
	+------------+------+-------+-----------+
	|@{"   Clear   " LINK "EditToolClear"}|@{"     Fill     " LINK "EditToolClear"}|@{"   Abort   " LINK "EditToolClear"}|
	+------------+--------------+-----------+

Range : - >All< will affect the whole Map
        - >View< will affect only the area you see in the Edit-Window.
       
Layers: - >All< will affect all Layers
        - >Actual< will affect only the actual Layer.
        

o CLEAR will clear using the transparent Block.

o FILL will fill using the actual Block/Group of Blocks/Brush

o ABORT will close the window


@{B}Note:@{UB} If you are in @{" Brush-Mode " LINK "EditToolBrush"} then when selecting <FILL> and
      <ALL-LAYERS> then the affected Layers are:

		ActualLayer .. [ActualLayer+Number Layers of Brush-1]
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolUndo "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Undo"
@PREV "EditToolClear"
@NEXT "EditToolLayer"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: u

Undos the last action if the Menu @{" Settings/No Undo-Buffer " LINK "MSNoUndoBuffer"} is not
activated.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EditToolLayer "Edit-Screen: ToolWindow.Layers"
@PREV "EditToolUndo"
@NEXT "EditToolWindow"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Shortcut: <Number of Layer>

Sets the actual Layer in which Drawing-Operations (Brush-Cutting, Flipping,
... too!!) are to be done.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ProjectWindow "The Project Selection-Window"
@TOC "Manual"

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "Manual"}@{"PowerCrawler: ????        " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+---------------------------+
	| @{"ū" LINK ""} Map                    |
	| @{"ū" LINK ""} Brushs                 |
	| @{"ū" LINK ""} Settings               |
	| @{" " LINK ""} Filenames              |
	| @{" " LINK ""} Flip-Table             |
	| @{" " LINK ""} Mask                   |
	+---------------------------+
	| @{"  Confirm  " LINK ""} @{"   Abort   " LINK ""} |
	+---------------------------+
@ENDNODE

@NODE BrushWindow "Edit-Screen: Brush-Window"
@TOC "ManualEditingMaps"

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditToolWindow"}@{"Brush          " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+-------------+-+
	| Bridge      |@{BG SHINE} @{BG BACKGROUND}|
	| Waterfall   |@{BG SHINE} @{BG BACKGROUND}|
	| Wall        |@{BG SHINE} @{BG BACKGROUND}|
	|	      |@{BG SHINE} @{BG BACKGROUND}|
	|	      |@{BG SHINE} @{BG BACKGROUND}|
	+-------------+-+
	|@{"              " LINK ""}|
	+---------------+
	|@{" New   " LINK ""}@{"  Kill " LINK ""}|
	|@{" Sort  " LINK ""}@{"  Info " LINK ""}|
	+---------------+

In the BrushWindow you can add the actual Brush to the Brush-Table. To do
this click @{B}NEW@{UB} or press @{B}SPACE@{UB}. The Listview-String-Gadget where you can
enter a Name for the Brush will be activated.

You can change the Name of a Brush by selecting it and changing the Name in
the Listview-String-Gadget.

You can delete a selected Brush by clicking @{B}KILL@{UB} or pressing the @{B}DELKEY@{UB}.

You can get some information about the selected Brush by clicking @{B}INFO@{UB} or
pressing the @{B}HELP-KEY@{UB}.

The Brushes can be sorted (by their name) by clicking @{B}SORT@{UB} or pressing the
@{B}RETURN-KEY@{UB}.

To use a Brush from the Brush-Table either click at its name with the Mouse
or choose it from the @{" Special-Window's " LINK "EditSpecialWindow"} Brush-PopUp-Menu!

You can use the Cursor-Keys to scroll through the Listview-Entries.


@{B}  !! YOU DON'T HAVE TO CLOSE THE BRUSH-WINDOW TO CONTINUE MAP-EDITING !!
  !!                    IT WORKS ASYNCHRONOUSLY                       ||@{UB}
@ENDNODE

@NODE LineSettings "Edit-Screen: Line-Settings"
@PREV "EditToolWindow"
@NEXT "AirSettings"
@TOC "EditToolWindow"

Click twice the Line-Gadget to bring up the Settings-Window.
There are three Modes. I'll explain how they work with an Example.

Your actual Group of Blocks (5 x 5 Blocks selected from the Blocks-Screen)
looks like this.
			@{BG SHINE} :   @{BG BACKGROUND}
			@{BG SHINE}/»»\\ @{BG BACKGROUND}
			@{BG SHINE}|»»|T@{BG BACKGROUND}
			@{BG SHINE}|oO||@{BG BACKGROUND}
			@{BG SHINE}»»»»»@{BG BACKGROUND}

