@NODE EMBFlipX "Edit-Screen: Menus.Brush.Flip X"
@PREV "EditMenuBrush"
@TOC "EditMenuBrush"

Flips the actual Block/Brush hor. using the Flip-Table if there is one.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMBFlipY "Edit-Screen: Menus.Brush.Flip Y"
@TOC "EditMenuBrush"

Flips the actual Block/Brush vert. using the Flip-Table if there is one.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMBackDrop "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settings.Backdrop"
@PREV "EditMenuSettings"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

Changes the look of the Map-Window:

	Standard: You get a standard sizeable Window with Scrollers

	Backdrop: The window is borderless, has no Scrollers and its size
		  can't be changed!
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMToolBox "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settings.Toolbox"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

Opens or closes the Toolbox Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMHideS "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settings.Hide Special Window"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

If active the Special Window will always be put to the back (it gets in-
visible). This has only effect if the Map Window is in Backdrop-Mode. In
normal Mode the Special Window is the only Backdrop-Window on Screen and
therefore always in background.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMTransparentBrush "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settings.Transparent Brush"
@NEXT "EMUseFlipTable"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

If checked transparent Blocks will not be drawn (they don't affect the Map-
Buffer) if you are using a @{" Brush " LINK "EditToolBrush"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE EMUseFlipTable "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settings.Use Flip-Table"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

If checked the @{" Flip-Table " LINK "EMFlipTable"} (if there is one) will be used when doing
Flipping-Actions (@{" Flip X " LINK "EMFlipX"}, @{" Flip Y " LINK "EMFlipY"}).
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMSuperCursor "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settngs.Super-Cursor"
@NEXT "EMLayerControl"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

@{"   Never          " LINK ""}
@{" x Standard delay " LINK ""}
@{"   Always         " LINK ""}

In the Sub-Menu you can select between:

	@{B}Never         :@{UB} The Cursor will always be simple.

	@{B}Standard delay:@{UB} The Cursor will turn into the Super-Cursor after
	                the standard delay. The standard delay can be
	                changed in the @{" Tooltypes " LINK "TTMarkingTicks"}.

	@{B}Always        :@{UB} The Cursor will always be a Super-Cursor, meaning
			that you'll see immediately how the result will be
			when painting.

@{B}Note:@{UB} If the Super-Cursor is active then before doing the first Mouse-Click
      for drawing wait until the Super-Cursor is completely drawn otherwise
      the click might not be recognized (or recognized later when the mouse
      is already on a different place). Especially in Freemode-Drawing this
      may happen!
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMLayerControl "Edit-Screen: Menus.Settngs.Layer Control"
@NEXT "EditMenuSettings"
@TOC "EditMenuSettings"

Pops up the layer control requester, which allows you to turn off visibility
and transparency (= mask blitting) for certain layers. This should make
editing easier in some situations - the only purpose of the requester. The
real map/layer data is not affected by the settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMCopyBlocks "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Block -> Block"
@PREV "EditMenus"
@NEXT "EMSwapBlocks"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Function: Replaces one Block with another Block.

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Replace Block                   " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"      " LINK ""} @{"?" LINK ""}      >     @{"?" LINK ""} @{"      " LINK ""} |
	+----------------+---------------+
	|      Range     |     Layers    |
	|		 |		 |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} All        |  @{" " LINK ""} All        |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} View       |  @{" " LINK ""} Actual     | 
	+----------------+---------------+
	| @{"  Calculate  " LINK ""}   @{"    Exit!    " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+

Brings up a Window. In the two String-Gadgets you can enter the Source and
Destination Block-Number. By clicking on one of the @{"?" LINK "EMCopyBlocks"} you can select the
Block directly from the Blocks-Screen.

Range	 : >All< will affect the whole Map
           >View< will affect only the area you see in the Edit-Window.

Layers	 : >All< will affect all Layers
           >Actual< will affect only the actual Layer.

Calculate: Starts Block-Replacing.

Exit	 : Closes Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMSwapBlocks "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Block <-> Block"
@PREV "EMCopyBlocks"
@NEXT "EMCopyLayer"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Function: Swaps (exchanges) one Block with another Block.

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Swap Block                      " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"      " LINK ""} @{"?" LINK ""}     < >    @{"?" LINK ""} @{"      " LINK ""} |
	+----------------+---------------+
	|      Range     |     Layers    |
	|		 |		 |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} All        |  @{" " LINK ""} All        |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} View       |  @{" " LINK ""} Actual     | 
	+----------------+---------------+
	| @{"  Calculate  " LINK ""}   @{"    Exit!    " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+

Brings up a Window. In the two String-Gadgets you can enter the Source and
Destination Block-Number. By clicking on one of the @{"?" LINK "EMCopyBlocks"} you can select the
Block directly from the Blocks-Screen.

Range	 : >All< will affect the whole Map
           >View< will affect only the area you see in the Edit-Window.

Layers	 : >All< will affect all Layers
           >Actual< will affect only the actual Layer.

Calculate: Starts Block-Swapping.

Exit	 : Closes Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMCopyLayer "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Layer -> Layer"
@PREV "EMSwapBlocks"
@NEXT "EMSwapLayer"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Function: Replaces one Layer with another Layer.

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Replace Layer                   " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"      " LINK ""} @{"?" LINK ""}      >     @{"?" LINK ""} @{"      " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+
	|      Range                     |
	|		  		 |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} All                         |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} View                        |
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"  Calculate  " LINK ""}   @{"    Exit!    " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+

Brings up a Window. In the two String-Gadgets you can enter the Source and
Destination Layer.

Range	 : >All< will affect the whole Map
           >View< will affect only the area you see in the Edit-Window.

Calculate: Starts Layer-Replacing.

Exit	 : Closes Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMSwapLayer "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Layer <-> Layer"
@PREV "EMCopyLayer"
@NEXT "EMFlipX"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Function: Swaps (exchanges) one Layer with another Layer.

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Swap Layer                      " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"      " LINK ""} @{"?" LINK ""}     < >    @{"?" LINK ""} @{"      " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+
	|      Range                     |
	|		  		 |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} All                         |
	|  @{" " LINK ""} View                        |
	+--------------------------------+
	| @{"  Calculate  " LINK ""}   @{"    Exit!    " LINK ""} |
	+--------------------------------+

Brings up a Window. In the two String-Gadgets you can enter the Source and
Destination Layer.

Range	 : >All< will affect the whole Map
           >View< will affect only the area you see in the Edit-Window.

Calculate: Starts Layer-Swapping.

Exit	 : Closes Window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipX "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Flip X"
@PREV "EMSwapLayer"
@NEXT "EMFlipY"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Activates X-Flipping. Select the Range with the Mouse. Use the Cursor-Keys
to scroll the Map during Selection. RMB or disactivating the Map-Window
aborts! (Use the Keyboard to zoom!)

<RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON> leaves X-Flipping.

Check out @{" Use Flip-Table " LINK "EMUseFlipTable"} and @{" Flip-Table ... " LINK "EMFlipTable"}!

@{B}Hint:@{UB} <RETURN> selects the whole map.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipY "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Flip Y"
@PREV "EMFlipX"
@NEXT "EMCreateMapPreview"
@TOC "EditMenus"

Activates Y-Flipping. Select the Range with the Mouse. Use the Cursor-Keys
to scroll the Map during Selection. RMB or disactivating the Map-Window
aborts! (Use the Keyboard to zoom!)

<RIGHT MOUSE BUTTON> leaves Y-Flipping.

Check out @{" Use Flip-Table " LINK "EMUseFlipTable"} and @{" Flip-Table ... " LINK "EMFlipTable"}!

@{B}Hint:@{UB} <RETURN> selects the whole map.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMCreateMapPreview "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Create Map-Preview"
@PREV "EMFlipY"
@NEXT "EMFlipTable"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Function: Creates a Map-Preview in any Zoom (1% - 100%) which can be saved
          as IFF-ILBM.
          
	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Map-Preview                    " LINK ""}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+-------------------------------+
	|           Blocksize X - Y     |
	| @{"   16" LINK ""} @{"                   " LINK ""}@{"<" LINK ""}@{">" LINK ""} |
	| @{"   16" LINK ""} @{"                   " LINK ""}@{"<" LINK ""}@{">" LINK ""} |
	+-------------------------------+
	| @{" Range " LINK ""}  @{"   (0,0)-(99,99)   " LINK ""} |
	+-------------------------------+
	|    Screensize @{"  1600 x 1600  " LINK ""} |
	+-------------------------------+
	| @{"    Create    " LINK ""} @{"    Abort    " LINK ""} |
	+-------------------------------+

	
Brings up a Window where you can select the Width/Height in Pixel each
Block will be scaled to. >Screensize< shows you the Preview-Size you
will get with the actual Width/Height. By clicking the >Range< Gadget
you can select the Range (default is whole map)

Create	: Creates the Map-Preview. Use <ESC> to abort Preview-Drawing.
	  When finished use the Menus to save the Preview.
	  
Abort	: Aborts Map-Preview Creation (closes Window).
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipTable "Edit-Screen: Menus.Special-Operations.Fliptable ..."
@PREV "EMFlipY"
@NEXT "EditMenus"
@TOC "EditMenuSpecial"

Allows you to create, edit or kill a Flip-Table. A Flip-Table allows you to
do controlled Flipping-Actions. Example:

@{U}Source                  Normal Flip-X           Flip-X with Flip-Table@{UU}

@{BG SHINE}½|╗  <O@{BG BACKGROUND}			@{BG SHINE}O<  ╗|½@{BG BACKGROUND}			@{BG SHINE}O>  ½|╗@{BG BACKGROUND}
@{BG SHINE}_|/»\\_O@{BG BACKGROUND}			@{BG SHINE}O_\\»/|_@{BG BACKGROUND}			@{BG SHINE}O_/»\\|_@{BG BACKGROUND}



Brings up a Window which looks like this:

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EditMenuSpecial"}@{"Flip-Table            " LINK "EMFlipTable"}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+----------------------+
	| @{"    Create new      " LINK "EMFlipCreate"} |
	| @{"        Kill        " LINK "EMFlipKill"} |
	| @{"        Edit        " LINK "EMFlipEdit"} |
	+----------------------+

Don't forget to activate @{" Use Flip-Table " LINK "EMUseFlipTable"}!
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipCreate "Edit-Screen: Flip-Table.Create"
@PREV "EMFlipTable"
@NEXT "EMFlipKill"
@TOC "EMFlipTable"

Allocs a Flip-Table-Buffer and enters @{" Flip-Table-Editing " LINK "EMFlipEdit"}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipKill "Edit-Screen: Flip-Table.Kill"
@PREV "EMFlipCreate"
@NEXT "EMFlipEdit"
@TOC "EMFlipTable"

Kills the Flip-Table-Buffer (It will be removed from memory).
@ENDNODE

@NODE EMFlipEdit "Edit-Screen: Flip-Table.Edit"
@PREV "EMFlipKill"
@NEXT "EMFlipTable"
@TOC "EMFlipTable"

	@{BG FILL}@{"ū" LINK "EMFlipTable"}@{"Flip-Table              " LINK "EMFlipEdit"}@{BG BACKGROUND}
	+------------------------+
	| +--------+  +--------+ |
	| |        |  |        | |
	| |@{BG SHINE}<SOURCE>@{BG BACKGROUND}|  |@{BG SHINE}<FLIP X>@{BG BACKGROUND}| |
	| |        |  |        | |
	| +--------+  +--------+ |
	| @{"         " LINK "EMFlipEdit"}   @{"         " LINK "EMFlipEdit"} |
	| +--------+             |
	| |        |      @{"ū" LINK "EMFlipEdit"}     |
	| |@{BG SHINE}<FLIP Y>@{BG BACKGROUND}|    AB=BA    |
	| |        |             |
	| +--------+             |
	| @{"         " LINK "EMFlipEdit"}             |
	+------------------------+
	| @{"                  " LINK "EMFlipEdit"}@{"<" LINK "EMFlipEdit"}@{">" LINK "EMFlipEdit"} |
	+------------------------+

<Flip X> and <Flip Y> are the Destination Blocks.

By clicking in one of the Block-Fields you can activate the Blocks-Screen
and select a Block directly from it. You can also enter its number in one
the String-Gadgets if you know it.

If <AB=BA> is activated then when selecting a <Destination-Block> for the
<Source-Block> then the <Destination-Block>'s <Destination-Block> will be
set automatically to <Source-Block>. Confused? Well, here's an example:

	o Source = 10
	o You Select 30 as Flip-X (Destination-X)
	o Block 30 will automatically get 10 as Flip-X (Destination-X)

The Scroll-Gadget at the bottom of the windows controls the <Source-Block>.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ManualConcept "The Concept of PowerCrawler"
@TOC "Manual"
To edit a map you first have to load an image which contains the Blocks.
Supported formats are IFF-ILBM and any format supplied by your installed
DATATYPES. Look at @{" Menus " LINK "MainMenuSettings"} to see how to change the Picture-Load-
Routine (there's no autodetecting!). The size of the Blocks can be from
@{b} 1 x 1 @{ub} upto @{b} 255 x 255 @{ub}. Each Block is given a number that starts
with 0 (upper left corner) and increases by one when going right.

@{b}Note:@{ub} If the last Block on the right border doesn't fit exactly then it
      will be skipped.
      
      The program does this
      
       WIDTH OF BLOCK-PICTURE IN PIXEL
       -------------------------------
       WIDTH OF BLOCK IN PIXEL
       
      cutting any decimals to calc the number of Blocks horizontally.
      

@{b}Example:@{ub} Your picture has a size of 320 x 256 and you use 16 x 16 Blocks.
	 The numbers given to the Blocks are like this:
	 
	 [  0] [  1] [  2] [  3] [...] [...] [ 18] [ 19]
	 [ 20] [ 21] [ 22] [ 23] [...] [...] [ 38] [ 39]
	 [ 40] [...] [...]  ...
	 [...]  ...
	 [...]  ...
	  ...
	  ...
	 [300] [301] [302] [303] [...] [...] [318] [319]
	 

@{b}Note:@{ub} If your Map is in Byte-Mode then the program won't check if you pick
      up a Block with a number greater than 255. It will automatically cut
      it to a byte. (256 becomes 0, 280 becomes 24, ...)

The picture can also contain a mask (integrated in the IFF-ILBM-File or
loaded by "Hand") which will be used when your map has more than one layer.
In this case the Blocks in the layer 2, 3, 4, ... (depending how much
layers you use) will be "blitted" using the Mask (just like the Matte-Mode
in DPaint). See @{" Mask " LINK "ManualMask"} for more details about that!

After having load the picture and done the @{"Map-Settings" LINK "ManualMapSettings"} you can enter
the @{" Edit-Mode" LINK "ManualEditingMaps"} using the according Gadget or Menu.

@ENDNODE
